Ashwini Anburajan is a serial entrepreneur and writer living in New York. She's successfully bootstrapped ad tech startups -- Social Data Collective and OpenUp -- that have worked with major media companies and Fortune 500 brands. She's done original research into consumer behavior, featured multiple times on CNBC. Prior to that she worked for BuzzFeed, NBC News and consulted for large media companies. Anburajan helped lead the tokenization effort for 22X Fund and received an "Innovation in Venture Fundraising Award" from Microsoft for her work. She currently focuses on how blockchain can democratize access to capital and expand opportunity globally.

author: Ashwini_Anburajan;
title: How cryptocurrency can help start-ups get investment capital

aws-transcripts.transcript: when I was raising investment from my start up, a venture capitalist said to me, Ashwini, I think you're gonna raise a few $1,000,000 your company, it's gonna sell for 50 to 70,000,000. You're gonna be really excited. You're early. Investors are gonna be really excited, and I'm gonna be really upset. Some not gonna invest in this deal. I remember just being dumb Struck would be unhappy with putting 4 $5,000,000 into a company and having it sell for 50 to 70,000,000. I was a first time founder. I didn't have a wealthy network of individuals to turn to for investment. So I went to venture capitalists the most common form of investor in a technology company. But I've never taken the time to understand what was motivating that VC to invest. I believe we're living in a golden era of entrepreneurship. There is more opportunity to build companies than ever before, but the financial systems designed to fund that innovation venture capital they haven't evolved in the past 20 to 30 years. Venture capital was designed to pour large sums of money into a small number of companies that can sell for over $1,000,000,000. It was not designed to sprinkle capital across many companies that have the potential to succeed. But for less like my own, that limits the number of ideas that get funded, the number of companies that are created and who can actually receive that funding to grow. And I think it inspires a tough question. What's our goal? With entrepreneurship? If our goal is to create a tiny number, $1,000,000,000 company's let's stick with Venture Capital, it's working. But if our goal is to inspire innovation and empower more people to build companies of all sizes, we need a new way to fund those ideas. We need a more flexible system that doesn't squeeze entrepreneurs and investors into one rigid financial outcome. We need to democratize access to capital. In the summer 2017 I went out to San Francisco to join a tech accelerator with 30 other companies. The accelerator was supposed to teach us how to raise venture capital. When I got out there, the startup community was buzzing about I CEOs or initial coin offerings. For the first time, I CEOs had raised more money for young startups, then venture capital had. It was the first week of the program Tequila Friday, and the founders couldn't stop talking. I want to raise an icy Oh, I'm gonna raise an icy Oh, until one guy goes, How cool. If we did this all together, we should do an I C E O. That combines the value of all of our companies and raise money as a group. At that point, I had to ask. The obvious question Dies. What's an I C E O I. CEOs were away for young companies to raise money by issuing a digital currency tied to the value and service is that the company provides the currency act similar to shares in a company like on the public stock market, increasing in value as it's traded online. Most important, Ice Eos expanded the investor pool from a few 100 venture capital firms to millions of everyday people Excited to invest, this market represented more money. It represented more investors, which meant a greater likelihood to get funded. I was sold. The idea, though of doing it together, still seemed a little crazy. Startups compete with each other for investment.
